validated = FALSE scientific articles are typically early (older) papers that are missing both abstract and full text, and thus metadata cannot be entered (nor validated)

Select only Scientific Article (original research)

Moving forward with analyses

publs <- subset(publs, publication_type == "scientific" & publication_format == "article")
publs <- droplevels(publs)

Select validated publications

Subset the publication list to those that are validated (i.e., metadata validated by two different content editors) and those that are included_in_stats (i.e., as validated but only including publications representing (peer-reviewed) scientific articles presenting original data from mesophotic depths):

# use validated == "true" for file obtained directly from website,
# or validated == "TRUE" for static downloaded CSV file
# same for included_in_stats variable
publs <- subset(publs, validated == "TRUE") #publs_validated
publs <- subset(publs, included_in_stats == "TRUE") #publs_for_stats # Original data

Data analysis

Change in publication numbers over time

Calculate the fold-increase in publications From 2008 to 2023

publs_time_counts <- publs %>% #publs_validated
  group_by(publication_year) %>%
    dplyr::summarise(count=n()) %>%
      mutate(total_count = cumsum(count))

total_count <- publs_time_counts[publs_time_counts$publication_year==2023, "total_count"]/publs_time_counts[publs_time_counts$publication_year==2008, "total_count"]

total_count
##   total_count
## 1    4.753846

MCE specific

Publications by focus groups

Where fields have multiple values (through so-called HABTM associations), such as research_fields , they are separated by semicolons, for example: Ecology; Community structure; Disturbances.

Therefore, to query any of these fields, we need to separate these into individual rows. Then, we can plot for example the number of publications for each of those fields.

# Split `focusgroups` into new rows
publs_focusgroups <- separate_rows(publs, "focusgroups", sep=";\\s+") #publs_for_stats

# Remove rows with no associated `focusgroups`
publs_focusgroups <- publs_focusgroups[!
(is.na(publs_focusgroups$focusgroups) |
publs_focusgroups$focusgroups ==
""), ]

publs_focusgroups$focusgroups <- factor(publs_focusgroups$focusgroups)

However, there is overlap of locations that are present in both Before 2008 and 2009-2023 data

Cross check to only obtain unique locations

In summary, 54 MCE locations were both in Before 2008 and 2008-2023 categories Therefore 97 new locations 2008-2023 - 53 shared locations = 44 new MCE locations between 2008-2023 Note: 13 unique MCE locations that were only from Before 2008 (but not studied again in 2008-2023)

Grand total = 13 unique locations Before 2008 + 53 shared locations two time periods + 44 new MCE locations 2008-2023 + 1 La Perouse* + 1 Singapore* = TOTAL 112 unique MCE locations

La Perouse (publication 1642 - had both MCE and TME tags, but manually reviewed and it is a valid new location in 2023) Singapore (often without mesophotic tag because research at shallow depths, but included in database because low-light reef environment is relevant to mesophotic science)

## [1] 41

In summary, 18 TME locations were both in Before 2008 and 2008-2023 categories Therefore 41 new locations 2008-2023 - 18 shared locations = 23 new TME locations between 2008-2023

Therefore, 1 unique Before 2008 locations + 18 shared locations two time periods + 23 new 2008-2023 locations = 42 locations total
